text:
Growing up, Michael Burry obsessively studied investing.

As he read more and more about the topic, naturally, he came across the richest investor in the world, Warren Buffett.

And after he read everything there is to read about Buffett’s success, Burry was certain of 1 thing:

“If you are going to be a great investor,” Burry said, “you have to fit the style to who you are.”

“At one point I recognized that Warren Buffett, though he had every advantage in learning from Ben Graham, did not copy Ben Graham, but rather set out on his own path, and ran money his way, by his own rules.”

Takeaway 1:

To Burry, the big lesson from Buffett's success is that investors should match their style to their unique personality traits.

This is known in economics as “match quality”—the degree of alignment between the traits of a profession and the traits of a person.

When the musicians John Mayer and Cory Wong got together to play guitar, Mayer identified Wong as someone who has perfectly fit his playing style to his physical and mental traits.

Mayer said he had watched a bunch of videos of Wong playing guitar, and as he did, he watched Wong’s right hand—his strumming hand.

“You have an anatomy thing working for you with your right hand,” Mayer said. “Your right hand is shaped in a way—you have long fingers, very sinewy hands—that allows you to play like that.”

Wong’s anatomy and his playing style are completely aligned, Mayer says.

“And I wish more players would embrace finding their strengths are anatomically—the way your hand is shaped, the way your mind works, etc.—and play to those strengths.”

Takeaway 2:

Buffett studied the greats that came before him, but he didn’t copy them. Instead, as Burry said, he took what he learned to form his own style.

This strategy works beyond just the world of investing.

It's said, for instance, that the filmmaker Quentin Tarantino knows so much about his filmmaking heroes that he could write their biographies.

“Whether it be Brian de Palma or Howard Marks or Douglas Sirk or Scorcese,” Tarantino explains, “I would just obsess about filmmakers the way a baseball fan might obsess about their favorite baseball players.”

And yet, Tarantino movies are distinctly Tarantino—he set out on his own path, and made Movies his way, by his own rules.
